{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a9f201e3-9a1f-444a-b4d9-c98468d8e1a3","content":"## What Happened\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, the compiler's overload resolution changed due to **first-class span support**. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nThis is because the implicit conversion `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is considered *more specific* than `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees, and the expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) throws at runtime.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nForce the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by disambiguating:\n\n**Option A — Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly (non-extension syntax):**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth approaches pin the resolution to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is expression-tree-safe. Option A is less invasive if you have many call sites; Option B is more explicit about intent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61519c4b-c8af-4368-81ed-55396bb8a10f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to how the compiler resolves extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension members** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), and as part of this, the compiler changed how it resolves certain method calls.\n\nActually, let me think more