 and that's what's breaking the expression tree evaluation.\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a more specific type than `IEnumerable<T>`, the compiler prefers the span version. But expression trees can't contain ref struct operations, so when the lambda is compiled, it should fail at compile time—though the user reports a runtime error, which suggests the expression tree is being created successfully but fails when executed. error because expression trees can't use ref structs. But the user says it throws at runtime, so maybe they're constructing the expression tree manually, or there's something else going on. Let me consider if .NET 10 changed how the expression tree interpreter handles method invocations—perhaps the `Contains` method now uses `Span`-based implementations internally, and the interpreter has trouble invoking those through reflection.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be simpler: C# 14 introduced new extension member lookup rules that could change how `array.Contains(num)` resolves. Previously it would find `Enumerable.Contains` via extension method lookup, but now a different method might be resolved first. Or .NET 10 added new BCL overloads that changed the resolution entirely. The most likely culprit is implicit span conversions that were fully enabled in C# 13 but may have had expression tree carve-outs that are now gone in C# 14. The compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` because arrays implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, but since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it can't be used in expression trees—that's what causes the runtime failure. The solution is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload resolution. Maybe the expression tree interpreter fails when it tries to invoke the method because the method signature or behavior changed in .NET 10—perhaps `Enumerable.Contains` now has a specialized overload for arrays that uses spans internally, or the BCL added an instance method directly on arrays, shifting how the method gets resolved and breaking the expression tree's expectations. conversion to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now preferred over `IEnumerable<T>` during overload resolution, but since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct that can't be used in expression trees, this causes the compilation error. The workaround is to explicitly cast to `IEnumerable<int>` or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly to force the older overload. I'm trying to figure out whether this is a new issue in C# 14 or if C# 13 already had this problem, since span support was introduced earlier. But in an expression tree context with a ref struct involved, it would fall back to `Enumerable.Contains` or throw an error. In C# 14, that fallback behavior might have changed—either the compiler now errors outright or the expression tree fails at runtime when the interpreter tries to execute a `MethodCallExpression` referencing `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with a `ReadOnlySpan`, since it can't construct that span in the interpreted context. I'll go with this explanation as the most likely scenario.\n\nThe key distinction is that `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` uses the expression tree interpreter, which walks the tree node by node and can't handle ref struct parameters or return types, whereas `Compile(preferInterpretation: false)` uses IL emission and would handle the span-based method directly. So the compiler in C# 14 probably resolves `Contains` to the `MemoryExtensions` overload, but the interpreter fails when it tries to evaluate that call. The real issue is that C# 14 / .NET 10 changed overload resolution to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays due to implicit span conversion being a better match, but this breaks expression trees since they can't handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameters. I can fix this by explicitly casting to `IEnumerable<int>` or calling `Enumerable.Contains` directly...\n